<div class="welcome">
Welcome to ECS, the School  of Electronics and Computer Science at the University of Southampton. ECS is one of the world's leading centres for 
<a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/research/">research</a>, 
<a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/about/teaching/">teaching</a>, <a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/business/">enterprise and innovation</a> in Electronics, Electrical Engineering and Computer Science.
<div class="sig">Head of School: <a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/people/wh">Professor Wendy Hall</a></div>
</div>


<div class="headline"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/466"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_466_img&amp;maxw=200&amp;maxh=150&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=e98165fb84727c768301e09e50f9abed" alt="Neural network image" border="0" width="200" height="71" class="thumbnail" /></a><h2>Headline News</h2><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/466">Agent technologies will boost business efficiency</a></h3><p>This year's Agent Technology Conference, taking place in Zurich on Friday 1 October, will bring together world-leading agent technology experts and representatives from traditional industries to report on how they are using autonomous computer agents to perform functions in the workplace. The conference is co-ordinated by the School of Electronics and Computer Science, working with colleagues at the University of Liverpool.</p></div><div id='contentMain'>
<hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/463"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_463_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=1b86805926fce8011b81da1ef9feb0bc" alt="Professor White looks on as the agreeement is signed between the University and IP2IPO" border="0" width="120" height="105" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/463">'Energy harvest' startup aims to power wireless systems</a></h3><p>Perpetuum, a new spin-out company from the School of Electronics and Computer Science, has raised capital from the venture capitalists, IP2IPO Group plc. Perpetuum is developing integrated microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) that harvest vibrational energy from the environment, which can then release the energy to run systems. The company aims to address the desire for small, lower power and wireless electronic devices, many of which currently depend on batteries.</p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/462"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_462_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=b740da8cfaedab2754a24a8c131d5c5f" alt="The new MailScanner book" border="0" width="97" height="120" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/462">MailScanner development could ease spam scourge</a></h3><p>A new anti-spam feature devised by MailScanner mastermind, Julian Field of the School of Electronics and Computer Science, could lessen the amount of junk mail that companies and individuals receive. The new development works by using a spam filtering system which scores messages, deleting those which are the most ‘spammy’ and wrapping the remaining ones in other messages so that if they happen to be offensive, the recipient is shielded from the full impact. A new Guide to MailScanner will be published this month for its thousands of users worldwide.</p><p></p></div><hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/449"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_449_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=4be042a1d5c06999252e49261bd08655" alt="Neil Palmer demonstrates the power of the HV Lab" border="0" width="120" height="81" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/449">Power engineers switch to unique new lab</a></h3><p>Last year's widely disruptive power cuts in the UK, Europe and the United States demonstrated the extent to which we rely on electricity, and the catastrophic consequences to all aspects of our lives when the supply fails. A unique facility  opened this month at the University of Southampton is intended to help avoid these damaging incidents by providing the specialized research and testing facilities on which the power supply industry depends.</p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/443"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_443_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=1dbda7164e61bccbc99362922568e757" alt="James Wilkinson, Ping Hua and Patrick Hole" border="0" width="120" height="79" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/443">European water directive: optical sensors tackle pollutants</a></h3><p>Minute amounts of organic pollutants, including oestrone, can now be detected in river water as a result of a new optical sensing instrument realised in a project funded by the EU's Environment Programme. Professor James Wilkinson, left, with Ping Hua and Patrick Hole, of the Optoelectronics Research Centre, leads one of the AWACSS research teams which have developed the new instrument.</p></div><p class="clearBoth"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041013085439/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/">More News</a></p></div>

